'''Miyama Shrine''' (御山神社, ''Miyama Jinja'') is a [[Shinto shrine]] located on [[Miyajima]] ({{ill|Itsukushima|ja|厳島|12=draft}}) in [[Hatsukaichi, Hiroshima|Hatsukaichi]], [[Hiroshima Prefecture]], Japan. It serves as the '''Okumiya''' (inner shrine) of {{ill|Itsukushima Shrine|ja|厳島神社|12=draft}} and is situated near the '''summit of Mount Misen'''.

== Deities ==
Like '''Itsukushima Shrine''', Miyama Shrine enshrines the '''Three Munakata Goddesses''' ({{ill|Munakata Sanjojin|ja|宗像三女神|1=Three Munakata Goddesses|12=draft}}):
* {{ill|Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|ja|市杵島姫命|1=Ichikishimahime|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Tagorihime-no-Mikoto|ja|田心姫命|1=Tagorihime|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Tagitsuhime-no-Mikoto|ja|湍津姫命|12=draft}}

== History ==
According to tradition, '''Taira no Kiyomori''' ({{ill|Taira no Kiyomori|ja|Taira no Kiyomori|12=draft}}) constructed the shrine as the '''Okumiya (inner shrine) of Itsukushima Shrine'''.

Until the '''Edo period''', the shrine was known as the '''Sanki-dō''' (三鬼堂) and enshrined the '''[[Sanki Daigongen|Three Demon Gods]]''' (三鬼神, ''Sanki Shin''): 
* '''Suichō-oni Shin''' (追帳鬼神)
* '''Mara-oni Shin''' (魔羅鬼神)
* '''Jibi-oni Shin''' (時眉鬼神)

However, after the '''Shinbutsu Bunri''' ({{ill|Separation of Shinto and Buddhism|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}}) decree during the '''Meiji era''', the Sanki-dō was renamed '''Miyama Shrine''', enshrining the Munakata goddesses. The '''Sanki-dō''' itself was relocated and rebuilt near the '''Misen Main Hall''' ({{ill|Misen Hondo|ja|弥山本堂|12=draft}}).

== Shrine Grounds ==
The shrine features '''three single-bay Nagare-zukuri halls''', arranged in a '''品 (hin) shape''' to enshrine the three goddesses.

== Access ==
* '''From Miyajima Ropeway Shishiiwa Station''', it is about a '''30-minute hike''' via the '''Misen Main Hall'''.

== Related Articles ==
