* {{ill|Ichikishima-hime-no-Mikoto|ja|市杵島姫命|1=Ichikishima-hime|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichikishima-hime-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichikishima-hime||1=Ichikishima-hime|2=fr|3=Ichikishimahime|4=ja|5=イチキシマヒメ|6=zh|7=市寸島比賣命|8=ru|9=Итикишима-химэ|10=de|11=Ichikishima-hime}}
* {{ill|Tagorihime-no-Mikoto|ja|田心姫命|1=Tagorihime|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagorihime-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagorihime|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タキリビメ}}
* {{ill|Tagitsuhime-no-Mikoto|ja|湍津姫命|1=Tagitsuhime|2=ja|3=タギツヒメ|4=zh|5=多岐都比賣命|6=fr|7=Tagitsuhime|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagitsuhime-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagitsuhime|qq=}}

== History ==
According to tradition, '''Taira no Kiyomori''' ([[Taira no Kiyomori]]{{citation needed |Taira no Kiyomori|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taira no Kiyomori|qq=}}) constructed the shrine as the '''Okumiya (inner shrine) of Itsukushima Shrine'''.

Until the '''Edo period''', the shrine was known as the '''Sanki-dō''' (三鬼堂) and enshrined the '''[[Sanki Daigongen|Three Demon Gods]]''' (三鬼神, ''Sanki Shin''): 
* '''Suichō-oni Shin''' (追帳鬼神)
* '''Mara-oni Shin''' (魔羅鬼神)
* '''Jibi-oni Shin''' (時眉鬼神)

However, after the '''Shinbutsu Bunri''' ({{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|en|Shinbutsu bunri|qid=Q1970535|lt=Separation of Shinto and Buddhism|1=Shinbutsu bunri}}) decree during the '''Meiji era''', the Sanki-dō was renamed '''Miyama Shrine''', enshrining the Munakata goddesses. The '''Sanki-dō''' itself was relocated and rebuilt near the '''Misen Main Hall''' ({{ill|Misen Hondo|ja|弥山本堂|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Misen Hondo|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}).

== Shrine Grounds ==
The shrine features '''three single-bay Nagare-zukuri halls''', arranged in a '''品 (hin) shape''' to enshrine the three goddesses.

== Access ==
* '''From Miyajima Ropeway Shishiiwa Station''', it is about a '''30-minute hike''' via the '''Misen Main Hall'''.

